	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f104525035828971><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=5&mid=104525035828971>RE: decision...</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=5&mid=104525035828971#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=145263><span id=Scholar>lunaticfringesk</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>274 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Feb 14th 2:50 PM 2003</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.48]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Your message seems to suggest that a WAR will outdamage a SK by a significant amount.&nbsp;&nbsp;If so, I can tell you that that is absolutely not true. A WAR will NOT outdamage a SK *hands down*, especially if we are talking about comparing a 65SK to a 65WAR (all things as equal as they can get).  Ive read some parsings comparing the two and it just is illogical for VI to have these classes perform materially different in terms of DPS.<br><br>Especially at 65, an SK has spells that can crank out DPS (well, for a melee/hybrid class that is).  The introduction of PoP has changed the way the SKs perform.  The spells now are usually fast/faster casting spells that ususally are either mana heavy or have long re-cast times as their drawbacks.  You can, however, get them successfully cast in combat though.  VI couldnt leave the SK solely with (substantially) hand-be down NEC spells, as the cast time on those were just unreasonable for an SK.  Try casting Bond of Death on an unslowed mob (when you are MT) in any tier 2 or above PoP zone.  Trust me, it is a royal pain.<br><br>In terms of DPS, lets look at some of the 61+ SK spells:<br><br>Blood of Hate:  25 DPS and can get off on an unslowed mob frequently.  Terrific spell--one of my favorites next to festering darkness<br>Festering Darkness:  8 DPS.  Can also get off relatively easy on unslowed mob. Agro, snare, DoT---this spell has it all.<br>Spear of Decay:  13 DPS (recast time KILLS this spell, but a 600DD is damn good).  Gotta love the .5 sec cast time, but geez--45 secs for a re-cast? /sigh<br>Ignite Blood:  9 DPS.  Can also get off relatively easy on unslowed mob.  This spell is seldom resisted, making it a nice spell to cast.  The long duration, however, kinda kills it, as it seldom goes the full effect.  Nice to have though.<br><br>That is 55DPS and I will cast these on almost every mob (unless Im bottin--then its a little more challenging, as my attention is on more then just my SK).  The resist rate is low, even in PoP zones, and the cast times are reasonable, if not terrific.  That 55 DPS.  That isnt even factoring in weapon damage, which many are now noting just how much damage hybrids can to with the *insane* 2H weapons in ssra and PoP.  A WAR will have a hell of a time matching that DPS with his primary hand weapon (we are assuming he is DW, rite?), to say nothing about his offhand.  Factor in our weapon damage, things get very interesting indeed.<br><br>Further, in some zones, especially if Im not pulling, Im breaking out good-ole Zabaner (or whomever my pet name is) for even more DPS.<br><br>Lastly, if we are talking about a single fight, and HT is up, I almost challenge any class to outdamage an SK.  With UT 3 doing 4k damage instantly, that is downright scary.<br><br>Also, I may have chosen a *bad* word, that being *mitigate*.  Seldom will a WAR *mitigate* damage better then an SK, save for defensive and evasive.  For the most part, WAR/SK get all the same AAs up until class type abilities, in which both get some nice offensive/defensive capabilities.  In general, however, a WAR doesnt *mitigate* (or lessen) damage received any better than an SK.  They can just take a bigger beating, which is vastly important sometimes.<br><br>At the end of the day, WAR will not gain a huge, if any at all, advantage in DPS, nor do they *mitigate* damage substantially any better.  They can take the biggest beating though, no question about it and that, sometimes, is exactly what you are looking for.<br><br>Luna<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
